      {
        "type": "text",
        "text": "Here are the results for the paper **\"Deep Learning is Robust to Massive Label Noise\"** by David Rolnick, Andreas Veit, Serge Belongie, and Nir Shavit (arXiv:1705.10694, 2017):\n\n## Paper Overview\n\n"
      },
      {
        "citations": [],
        "type": "text",
        "text": "The authors are David Rolnick, Andreas Veit, Serge Belongie, and Nir Shavit"
      },
      {
        "type": "text",
        "text": ", affiliated with "
      },
      {
        "citations": [],
        "type": "text",
        "text": "Massachusetts Institute of Technology, Google Inc., and Cornell University"
      },
      {
        "type": "text",
        "text": ".\n\n### Key Findings\n\n"
      },
      {
        "citations": [],
        "type": "text",
        "text": "The paper shows that deep neural networks are capable of generalizing from training data for which true labels are massively outnumbered by incorrect labels, demonstrating remarkably high test performance after training on corrupted data from MNIST, CIFAR, and ImageNet."
      },
      {
        "type": "text",
        "text": "\n\n"
      },
      {
        "citations": [],
        "type": "text",
        "text": "Successful learning is possible even with an essentially arbitrary amount of noise. For example, on MNIST they find that accuracy of above 90 percent is still attainable even when the dataset has been diluted with 100 noisy examples for each clean example."
      },
      {
        "type": "text",
        "text": "\n\n"
      },
      {
        "citations": [],
        "type": "text",
        "text": "Such behavior holds across multiple patterns of label noise, even when erroneous labels are biased towards confusing classes."
      },
      {
        "type": "text",
        "text": "\n\n### Approach\n\n"
      },
      {
        "citations": [],
        "type": "text",
        "text": "Their work differs from prior approaches in that they do not aim to clean the training dataset or propose new noise-robust training algorithms. Instead, they study the behavior of standard neural network training procedures in settings with massive label noise."
      },
      {
        "type": "text",
        "text": "\n\n"
      },
      {
        "citations": [],
        "type": "text",
        "text": "Further, they show how the required dataset size for successful training increases with higher label noise."
      },
      {
        "type": "text",
        "text": "\n\n### Impact\n\n"
      },
      {
        "citations": [],
        "type": "text",
        "text": "According to Semantic Scholar, the paper has received 579 citations, with 29 highly influential citations."
      },
      {
        "type": "text",
        "text": "\n\n### Links\n- **arXiv**: https://arxiv.org/abs/1705.10694\n- **PDF**: https://arxiv.org/pdf/1705.10694\n- **Semantic Scholar**: https://www.semanticscholar.org/paper/96f4d4fc345698b9b44f034c0d63b704772c8386"
      }
